    Retire PR #95/#96/#98 wrapper code; defer to PR #93 native DFlash impl
    
    Per user 'go' confirmation 2026-06-09 to merge PR #93 to main. PR #93
    ships the production-grade native DFlash drafter implementation +
    alignment-trained baseline + cross-model speculative decoding eval +
    training pipeline. My PR #95/#96/#98 work shipped a parallel wrapper
    abstraction that turned out to be architecturally wrong (treated
    DFlash as standalone Qwen3 with own embed_tokens/lm_head/tokenizer,
    when DFlash by design shares all three with the verifier).
    
    This PR is the additive deliverable that:
    
      (a) keeps the two non-conflicting bits from my work (transformers
          pin drop + mlx_lm load diagnostic), and
      (b) is staged to flip its base from PR #93's branch to main once
          PR #93 lands, leaving a clean main + retirement-PR delta.
    
    PRs #95, #96, #98 will be marked SUPERSEDED via PR description
    updates and closed manually after PR #93 merges.
    
    Two changes carried into this retirement PR:
    
    1. requirements.txt — drop transformers <5.0 upper pin
    
       K3 critical path needs transformers 5.0+ for Gemma 4 verifier
       loading (used by both PR #93's k3_dflash_specdecode_eval.py and
       k3_dflash_alignment_train.py, plus the existing k3_feasibility_
       smoke.py CUDA verifier path). The original cap existed solely
       for the legacy Qwen3 dLM proposer (dllm-hub/Qwen3-0.6B-diffusion-
       mdlm-v0.1) whose custom modeling file uses 4.x decoder_layer.
       attention_type API. Pin drop is honest: the legacy Qwen3 dLM
       path will likely raise AttributeError under 5.x, but it's not
       on the K3 critical path. Affected legacy paths documented
       inline in the requirements.txt comment so K2.B Qwen backport
       (post-K3) can author a compat patch when that path resumes.
    
    2. scripts/research/k3_feasibility_smoke.py — mlx_lm.load
       structured diagnostic
    
       Adds _diagnose_mlx_load_failure(verifier_path, exc) helper that
       builds a JSON-serialisable diagnostic dict containing:
         * full Python traceback
         * config.json content (most likely place upstream bug fires)
         * k3_setup_manifest.json (records which HF id was downloaded)
         * files listing with sizes
         * mlx_lm.__version__
         * known_bug_fingerprints — auto-matched against:
             - bug1_quant_config_list_vs_dict
             - bug2_moe_expert_key_mismatch
             - bug3_ple_per_layer_input_handling
             - config_check_quantization_is_list
             - config_check_quantization_config_is_list
           Each fingerprint carries an evidence string + a
           suggested_workaround so the user can try a config.json edit
           BEFORE involving the agent for round-trip diagnosis.
    
       _load_verifier_mac wraps mlx_lm.load in a try/except that:
         1. Builds the diagnostic via _diagnose_mlx_load_failure
         2. Attaches it to the exception via setattr(e, 'kakeya_
            diagnostic', ...)
         3. Prints a human-readable matched-fingerprints summary to
            stderr (so the log tee shows the suggested workarounds
            without parsing JSON)
         4. Re-raises so main()'s existing handler still records
            verifier_load_FAIL
    
       main()'s verifier_load_FAIL handler reads the kakeya_diagnostic
       attribute (if set) and surfaces it in the JSON report under
       stage.diagnostic. Adds two summary fields:
         diagnostic_present: bool
         known_bug_fingerprints_matched: list[str]
    
       This is the only piece of PR #97 worth retaining — the rest of
       PR #97 was wrapper around PR #96's broken DFlashDrafter and
       gets retired.
    
