commit bec29cb353e37f4ab805c720b2a0779422256e05
Author: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>
Commit: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>

    ADR §11.11.13.7: fill in ctx70 row + close the Mac M4 empirical bound
    
    Per user-side ladder run 2026-06-09 commit f8646ee, evidence at
    results/research/k2a_production_smoke_ladder_mac_1781009878.json.
    
    The ladder produced the §11.11.13.7-pre-classified outcome (a):
    ctx70 hit + ctx280 miss → Mac M4 PyTorch MPS upper bound is
    bounded between ~1.4k and ~5.6k tokens; above that range,
    driver-allocated memory exceeds 24 GB physical and macOS swap
    thrashing dominates the latency.
    
    Filled-in §11.11.13.7 reference table:
    
      ctx_lines | tokens   | recall   | sec/token | driver alloc | arch_window | mem<24GB
      ----------|----------|----------|-----------|--------------|-------------|---------
      70        | ~1.4k    | 1/1 hit  | 1.98 s    | 23.49 GB     | 100 %       | ✓
      280       | ~5.6k    | 0/1 miss | 10.85 s   | 24.80 GB     | 100 %       | ✗
    
    Three additional readings codified in the prose:
    
    (4) Architecture works at BOTH rungs (effective_attention_fraction
        = 1.0 across ctx70 and ctx280). The dLM K/V Restoration
        mechanism is structurally correct on Mac MPS bf16 — the
        verifier attends to the full context regardless of whether
        physical memory holds. What breaks at ctx280 is the
        macOS swap I/O path, not the v0.4 architecture.
    
    (5) Latency penalty under swap is 5.5×: 1.98 s/token at ctx70
        (in-physical-memory) vs 10.85 s/token at ctx280 (over by
        ~0.8 GB). This is macOS swap I/O cost, not compute, not
        KL codec, not the K1.D / K2.A code path. Confirms the
        earlier diagnosis was right.
    
    (6) The 'in-memory' rung is tight: 23.49 GB of 24 GB physical
        at ctx70. The product fit-cap on this Mac box is strictly
        between ctx70 and ctx280, probably closer to 1.4k than to
        5.6k. A finer ladder (e.g. 70/140/200/280) could localise
        the crossover — but it's academic for the product question:
        anything in the 1.4k-5.6k band on Mac M4 24 GB PyTorch MPS
        already costs the user the entire 24 GB unified memory for
        one request, blocking the rest of the system.
    
    Codified the K3 product-success criterion (now falsifiable):
    
      K3 MLX must raise the in-physical-memory fit-cap from ≤ 1.4k
      tokens (PyTorch MPS today) to ≥ 100k tokens under the same
      single-request product shape, on equivalent 24 GB-class Mac
      hardware.
    
    When K3 MLX ships and the same ladder script is re-run (with
    --use-mlx-backend or whatever K3 introduces), the ctx280 row's
    driver_allocated_gb must drop below 24 GB AND recall_hit must
    become True for K3 to be considered product-viable on Mac.
    The ladder JSON schema is forward-compatible: re-running on
