Author: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>
Commit: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>

    K2.A.2 _V04SessionCache: complete HF Cache contract surface (transformers 4.57)
    
    Surfaces the bug the user hit on Mac mini 2026-06-09 v4:
    
        AttributeError: '_V04SessionCache' object has no attribute
                        'get_mask_sizes'
    
    at DLMRestoredVerifier._stateful_incremental_forward calling
    self.model(..., past_key_values=cache, ...) — transformers'
    masking_utils._preprocess_mask_arguments calls past_key_values.
    get_mask_sizes(cache_position, layer_idx) which our cache didn't
    implement.
    
    Root cause:
    
      K2.A.2 was implemented against an OLDER transformers Cache
      contract (4.x pre-mid-cycle). transformers 4.57 added
      get_mask_sizes() to the Cache base class. The K2.A.2
      implementation only defined get_seq_length and update —
      missing the now-required get_mask_sizes plus is_initialized
      (read by gemma3 modeling) and the deliberately-omitted
      is_sliding (which masking_utils gates on hasattr).
    
    Why this slipped through earlier:
    
      When this PR dropped the transformers <5.0 pin (commit ee166de
      in PR #95 / per ADR §11.15.3 prereq 1), the project advanced
      from transformers 4.45 (the original development pin floor)
      toward whatever 4.x is installed in the local environment —
      in this case 4.57. The pin drop was supposed to enable Gemma
      4 (transformers 5.0+), but as a side effect it also picked
      up newer 4.x Cache contract methods that K2.A.2 had no idea
      about. There was no contract audit, no upgrade gate, no
      test that flagged the new method.
    
    Audit performed (this PR):
    
      Read transformers' models/gemma3/modeling_gemma3.py and
      masking_utils.py, regex-extracted every method/attribute
      accessed on past_key_values:
    
          get_seq_length, is_initialized, update,
          get_mask_sizes, is_sliding
    
      Existing _V04SessionCache implements: get_seq_length, update.
      Missing: get_mask_sizes (required), is_initialized (required),
      is_sliding (deliberately omitted — see below).
    
    Fixes (3 changes to _V04SessionCache):
    
      (1) Add get_mask_sizes(cache_position, layer_idx) -> (kv_length,
          kv_offset). v0.4 update() returns the full assembled K/V
          tensor [B, kv_heads, T_full, head_dim] starting at position
          0, so kv_length = T_full and kv_offset = 0 for every layer.
    
      (2) Add is_initialized as a @property returning True. We
          construct _V04SessionCache fully populated (set_partition +
          set_evicted_kv per layer) BEFORE model.forward, so by the
          time gemma3 modeling reads this it IS initialised.
    
      (3) DELIBERATELY OMIT is_sliding. masking_utils gates ALL
          sliding-window logic on hasattr(past_key_values, 'is_sliding').
          Defining it would re-impose sliding masking on the already-
          merged v0.4 K/V tensor and mask out dLM-restored evicted
          positions — defeating the entire architecture. This is
          now documented inline at the Cache contract section of
          _V04SessionCache.
    
    Regression tests added (TestV04SessionCacheHFContract, 4 tests):
    
      test_implements_required_attribute_surface
        Direct existence check for the methods/properties required.
        Includes the inverse assertion that is_sliding is NOT
        present, with the architectural reason inline.
    
      test_get_mask_sizes_returns_full_t
        Constructs cache with cache_token_count_at_start=10,
        n_new_tokens=4. Asserts get_mask_sizes returns (14, 0)
        for any layer_idx.
    
      test_is_initialized_is_true
        Trivial sanity.
    
      test_audit_against_installed_transformers_source
        THE STRUCTURAL PROTECTION against future regressions of
        this kind. Reads the installed transformers' gemma3
        modeling + masking_utils source files, regex-extracts
        every method/attribute accessed on past_key_values, and
        validates that each name is in one of three classified sets:
    
          IMPLEMENTED         — present on _V04SessionCache
          DELIBERATELY_OMITTED — absent by architectural choice;
                                justification recorded inline
          SAFE_TO_IGNORE      — only called on specialised Cache
                                subclasses (HybridCache, etc.) we
                                never construct
    
        If a future transformers upgrade adds a new method NOT in
        any of these three sets, this test fails in CI with the
        new method's name in the error, instead of crashing on a
        real Mac mini run after the model has loaded. The error
        message tells the contributor exactly what to do:
        implement / classify / ignore.
    
      Verified: stashing the fixes and re-running this audit
      reproduces 4 failures with the missing-attribute names in
      the assertion text; un-stashing produces 4 PASS.
    
    Lessons codified:
    
      * Dropping the transformers pin (the K3 prereq 1 work) without
        auditing the Cache contract surface was the systemic mistake.
        Going forward, any future transformers version bump should
        re-run test_audit_against_installed_transformers_source
        locally BEFORE the bump lands.
    
      * The contract audit test approach (regex-extract method names
        from upstream source, validate against a code-recorded
        classification) is reusable for any HF interface we
        re-implement: Cache, AttentionInterface, ModelOutput, etc.
        When the next transformers upgrade adds methods to those
        interfaces, this test pattern catches it BEFORE production.
    
      * The K2.A.2 code review for PR #90 should have included a
        Cache contract audit. It didn't. We're paying for the
        omission in user-Mac-mini-runtime cycles 4 rounds in.
    
    Tests:
      tests/inference_engine/v04/: 287 passed (283 existing + 4 new
                                  HF contract regression tests)
    
    Co-authored-by: FluffyAIcode <FluffyAIcode@users.noreply.github.com>

