Author: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>
Commit: Cursor Agent <cursoragent@cursor.com>

    K3 Mac M4 pivot: download PLE-safe community 4-bit MLX variant instead of self-quantize
    
    User Mac M4 attempt at K3 self-quantize failed 2026-06-09 with:
    
      AttributeError: 'list' object has no attribute 'keys'
      exit_code=4
      Output dir empty (no valid 4-bit MLX model produced)
    
    Investigation diagnosis: this is bug #4 of 5 known mlx-lm /
    mlx-vlm bugs in handling Gemma 4 26B-A4B MoE quantization.
    Verified via:
    
      * GitHub issue ml-explore/mlx-lm#1123 (reproduction + analysis)
      * FakeRocket543/mlx-gemma4 write-up (5-bug enumeration + fixes
        merged into mlx-vlm 0.4.4 but not yet inherited by
        mlx-lm 0.31.3 Python API)
    
    The 5 interlocking bugs:
      1. ScaledLinear inherits nn.Module not nn.Linear → nn.quantize()
         can't find PLE layers
      2. Standard quantization quantizes PLE layers → 4-bit/8-bit
         output is degenerate (ionoxffionoxff... token-repetition)
      3. processor.save_pretrained() strips audio config → audio
         silently dropped
      4. SwitchLinear (MoE experts) not included in quantization →
         manifests as `'list' object has no attribute 'keys'` on
         26B-A4B (THIS bug is what user hit)
      5. embed_scale double-scaling → vision misalignment
    
    Fix: download the published PLE-safe community variant
    FakeRockert543/gemma-4-26b-a4b-it-MLX-4bit (16.4 GB; quantizes
    only large nn.Linear and SwitchLinear MoE expert layers; keeps
    ScaledLinear PLE / vision / norms / scalars in bf16; Apache 2).
    
    This commit:
    
    1. scripts/research/k3_quantize_for_mac.py — full rewrite
    
       New default: --mode download (fetches the community PLE-safe
       variant via huggingface_hub.snapshot_download). ~5-15 min
       on broadband.
    
       Preserved: --mode self-quantize (the original mlx_lm.convert
       path; expected to fail until mlx-lm catches up to
       mlx-vlm 0.4.4 fixes). Diagnostic improvements:
         - Captures full traceback to <output>.quantize_traceback.txt
           on failure (rather than just printing)
         - Warns at startup if mlx-lm version is < 0.21 (lazy loading
           needed for 24 GB Mac quantize)
         - Detects suspicious output sizes (< 14 GB indicates the
           MoE-not-quantized bug #4) and warns user to validate
         - Manifest schema bumped 1 -> 2 (adds 'mode', 'ple_safe_quantization',
           'rationale' fields)
    
    2. scripts/review_pr_k3_feasibility_on_mac.sh — Step 1
       instructions updated
    
       Old Step 1: "quantize verifier to 4-bit MLX (~30-90 min)"
       New Step 1: "download PLE-safe community variant (~5-15 min)"
    
       Note documents the 2026-06-09 pivot rationale and points to
       the upstream-bug source.
    
    3. ADR 0008:
    
       §11.15.2 Block A — Hardware feasibility, Mac M4 status
         Full rewrite documenting the 5 upstream bugs, the user's
         empirical failure, the community variant pivot, and the
         revised Mac M4 24 GB peak-memory estimate (22-26 GB at
         512-prompt smoke; tighter than original 18-22 GB estimate
         because the PLE-safe variant is correctly larger at 16.4
         GB vs the unsafe-naive ~13 GB).
    
       §11.14.3 candidates table
         New row: K3 Mac M4 path verifier (4-bit MLX) =
         FakeRockert543/gemma-4-26b-a4b-it-MLX-4bit (HF-verified
         2026-06-09, 16.4 GB, Apache 2).
    
       §11.15.10 risk register
         New row: "Mac M4 self-quantize broken on mlx-lm 0.31.3"
         marked "resolved 2026-06-09" with the pivot.
    
       §11.15.12 NEW — Lesson: don't self-quantize when a working
         community variant exists
         Generalised the K3 Mac M4 lesson: when a K-stage requires
         a quantized variant, FIRST check HF for community-published
         variants before committing to self-quantize. §11.14
         selection discipline now extends to quantized variants.
         Pattern: cutting-edge architectures have a window between
         "first publication" and "stable community quant" where
         stock library quantize paths are likely broken. Surveying
         before self-quantizing saves the quantize-and-debug cycle.
    
       §11.15.13 NEW — Lesson: verifier feasibility evidence is
         one half of Block A
         The K3 vast feasibility evidence (3f0557a) showed verifier
         load + forward succeeded; drafter forward failed only due
         to the smoke-script bug (NOT a model/hardware issue) which
         was fixed in PR #88. The lesson: smoke scripts must be
         robust to upstream tokenizer quirks (DFlash's
         trust_remote_code custom tokenizer was the surface here).
         Block A acceptance should not be gated on re-collecting
         drafter feasibility evidence at this near-miss scale.
    
    Tests:
      tests/inference_engine/v04/: 253 passed (no v04 code changes)
      AST parse: scripts/research/k3_quantize_for_mac.py OK
      bash -n: scripts/review_pr_k3_feasibility_on_mac.sh OK
    
    Compat:
      * Pure script + ADR change. No v04 code changes, no schema
        changes, no test changes.
      * Mac M4 setup workflow changes from "run quantize then smoke"
        to "run download then smoke". Same end-state, ~75% less time
        (5-15 min download vs 30-90 min quantize).
      * --mode self-quantize preserved as fallback for diagnostic
        use or future-mlx-lm-release recovery.
    
